## History of the Greek Language

The Greek language has one of the longest documented histories of any language still in use today, spanning more than 3,400 years of continuous written records.

The earliest attested form is **Mycenaean Greek**, written in a syllabic script called **Linear B** and preserved on clay tablets from around 1400–1200 BC. After the collapse of Mycenaean civilization, Greece entered a "Dark Age," and Linear B was forgotten. When literacy revived around 800 BC, the Greeks adapted the **Phoenician alphabet** — adding vowels — to create the Greek alphabet that became the foundation of all European writing systems.

The **Classical period** (c. 500–323 BC) produced the golden age of Athens: the philosophy of Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle; the tragedies of Sophocles and Euripides; the histories of Herodotus and Thucydides; and the oratory of Demosthenes. Attic Greek (the dialect of Athens) became the model of educated elegance and the standard for later study.

**Alexander the Great** (356–323 BC) spread Greek culture and language across the known world, from Egypt to the borders of India. Out of his conquests emerged **Koine Greek** — a simplified, standardized dialect that served as the Mediterranean world's common tongue for centuries. It was the language of the New Testament and the **Septuagint** (the Greek translation of the Hebrew Old Testament).

After the fall of the Western Roman Empire, Greek continued as the language of the **Byzantine Empire** (Eastern Rome) until its fall in AD 1453. **Modern Greek** descends from Byzantine Greek and is still spoken by roughly 13 million people today.

## The Greek Alphabet

The Greek alphabet has **24 letters** and is the direct ancestor of the Latin alphabet (and therefore English) as well as the Cyrillic script. Learning the alphabet is the essential first step for any student of Greek. Practice reading and writing each letter until it becomes automatic.

